transcript.text: Welcome back everyone.
Today we will be exploring range based pricing in on print shop.
In this video we will see how to add a product with a range based with the multiplication pricing method.
First of all, let's understand the significance of this pricing method.
Suppose you have a banner product and you would be charging your customers per unit they purchased, but not the whole quantity.
So for example, if a customer orders any quantity between 1:00 to 5:00, you will be charging $50.00 for each unit.
If the quantity ordered falls between 6:00 to 10:00, the per unit price decreases to $40, and so on.
However, when your customers order more quantities, the per unit price will decrease, which ultimately allows your customers to purchase more, eventually increasing your sales.
We have two pricing methods for this, range based with multiplication and range based without multiplication.
In the first one, when the customer places an order, the ordered quantity is multiplied by the unit price set for that particular range to derive the total payment price.
And in the later one, when the customer places an order, the price set for that quantity range becomes the payment price.
Let's create a product using a range based with multiplication pricing.
To begin, let's move to the admin panel.
Go to the product section and click on the Add button to create a product.
For creating any standard product, we have a video tutorial that you can follow on our help portal.
In the current video, we will focus on the range based pricing method.
So on the Add Product page, enter the relevant product details and select Range based with multiplication in the pricing method.
To define the pricing, first you need to define the product sizes in the Designer tab and move to the Price tab.
Here, enter the quantity range using the Add Price button, such as one to five, six to 1011 to 15, and 16 to 20.
Now enter the price for the per unit quantity 5040, thirty and $20 respectively.
Click on the Save and Continue button.
You can define the rest of the relevant details as per requirement and save everything.
Let's check how this will work in the storefront.
Now whenever the customer enters 7 as quantity, the system will look for the range and then the unit price of the quantity.
So 7 falls under the six to 10 range and the unit price will be $40 for the calculation.
The unit price will be multiplied by the quantity ordered which is $40 * 7 which will give a $280 price.

If you want your customers to enter the quantity only from the range where the minimum is 1 and the maximum is 20 and restrict them to enter anything less than or more than the specific range, then move to the Settings tab.
Here click on the Quantity tab and locate the Restrict Customer to order Quantity and enable this setting.
Save the changes on the front store.
You can now see this text informing the customers that they need to enter more than one and less than 20 quantities of the product.
When the customers enter anything out of this range, they will be notified by the system to enter a valid product quantity.
This is how the range based with multiplication works.
Now let's see how the product price is calculated when we have Range based without multiplication pricing method.
For this, let's just change the pricing method for the same product.
Go to the product edit page and from the price defining method drop down.
Select Range based without multiplication and click on Save and Continue.
We will keep the product size as it is and move to the Price tab.
As the pricing here will not be for individual units.
Let's just change the quantity as 50 to 100, then 101 to 150 and 151 to 200 and lastly 201 to 250.
Enter the pricing for the defined range as 180 sixty and $40 and then save the changes on the front end.
Let's just refresh the page and check the pricing.
As you can see, when the customer enters anything between 50 to 100, such as 70 or 92, the pricing remains the same.
The product quantity restriction will work the same for the new range defined.
This is how the range based pricing method works for your products in the on print shop.
If you have any questions, our support executives are here to help.
Just reach out through live chat on on printshop.com.
Thanks for tuning in.
